title: For Sale:  Reduced Price! 1940 German Luger Rig w/Holster, Belt, Tool and 2 clips
postcontent: 1940 WW2 German Luger with commercial markings. This gun was reworked probably in 1943 at the Inglestodt arms depot and reissued with the HZAJT20 stamp. At that time the breech would have been switched out with the current DWM toggle and the German Imperial Navy breech. The breech itself is very rare and sought after. All numbers match except firing pin and left grip which has an S/42 stamp. Original barrel with original strike marks and 655 acceptance stamp. The clips are non numbers matching, one is FXO P.08 with straight-wing 37 acceptance marks. The other is a WW1 clip with wooden base. The takedown tool is droop wing marked with I believe a 63 number. Holster is stamped 1915  H. Muller & Co, Offenbach a.M. and is in very good shape. You can tell this pistol has spent many years in this holster. The belt is in almost perfect shape with RZM 119 buckle markings signifying manufacture in Pforzheim by Eugen Schmiedhausler. Belt was not worn very long, the number 277 was inked stamped and still very visible along with hand inscriptions in German that I can make out but can't read and appear to be the owner's unit. I've researched this pistol through experts and these are the facts as I understand them. Please don't email just to tell me I'm wrong about any research, only contact me if you are interested in buying the gun. Lugers had many different variations and I don't claim to know everything. My photo files are too big to load so only one picture will be in the ad. Please ask and I will send you pics, I have a lot of them. Will take $1600 cash no trades or BS please.
